{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_hematite_ver01/data/sn88067047/00383344669/1946032901/0446.xml":{"full_text":"1\n0\nMissiscmni StanHr\u00bb**d\ndome Paper W*+h A Hon*'\nnewspcipe* o* *!iarnru*r. :irctfc\nEditor, That Tells State lat\u2019on and opinion, with raori\nNews Weekly fhap 10.00ft readers\nVOLUME XXIII THE WEEKLY ECHO FRIDAY, MARCH 29, 1946 _XI MB1.K M\nThe amnion Defenst I\nFor Trnerations Yet\n\nUnburn\nApril 12th marks the first anniver\nsary of the death of Franklin Delano\nRoosevelt.\nMr. Roosevelt had his political ene\nmies as indeed every great president\nof this country before him had his.\nj But, on this first anniversary of his\ndeath, friend and foe alike can join\nin acclaiming what Mr. Roosevelt said\nin a memorable address about the\nmeaning of America for us and for\nall mankind.\n\u201cFor more than three centuries we\nAmericans have been building on this\ncontinent a free society. A society\nin which the promise of the human\nspirit may find fulfillment. Com\nmingled here are the blood and gen\nius of all the peoples of the world\nwho have sought this promis--.\n\u201cWe have built well. We are con\ntinuing our efforts to bring the bless\nings of a free society, of a free and\nproductive economic system, to every\nfamily in the land. This is the prom\nf ise of America.\n\u201cIt is this that we must continue\nto build\u2014this that we must continue\nto defend.\n\"It is the task of our generation,\nyours and mine. But we build and\n\u25badefend not for our generation alone.\n^We defend the foundations laid down\nby our fathers. We build a life for\ngenerations yet unborn. We defend\nand we build a way of life, not for\nAmerica alone, but for all mankind.\u201d\nLAWRENCE\nDear Rev. Young: This will let the\nmany readers know that Sister M. L.\nTanner, a member of H. B. A. Lodge\nNo. 308 lost her house by fire and\neverything she had.\nShe is asking aid from the II. B. A.\nAr\\ amount given will be highly ,-ip\nprocir ed oy the lodge and all con\ncern'' You mo\u201d send it to Mrs. M\nr. ry, Law\u2019inee, Mis her pres\nident.\nWISDOM IN ELECTING AN\nEXECUTIVE BOARD, ETC.\nTo the presidents and readers of the\nEcho: It is a fine thing for us to take\nan inventory of our stock and see as\nto whether we are going forward or\nbackward. An inventory once p e r\nmonth will not be a dangerous thing\nin some concerns.\nAs your General Secretary, I have\nmade a close Observation of the REAL\nwork of the H. B. A. from July thru\nMarch 30, 1946 eight months.\nWe have held three Quarterly Boards\nsince the Convention and not in a\nsingle board has there been a decline\nin money, members and interest. The\nmembership has continued to increase,\nour collections have continued to in\ncrease, our deaths have increased and\nour payments on death benefits have\nincreased.\nMRS. BETTIE FAULKNER\nMrs. Bettie Faulkner of Ellisville,\npresident of H. B. A. Lodge No. 77\nis doing real H. B. A. work in her\nlodge.\nShe operates a first class Beauty\nparlor in Ellisville. In her March\nreport she reported for ninety nine\nmembers. Who said women couldn\u2019t\ndo things?\nSister \"Bettie\" you have almost\nreached the hundred mark.\nMRS. C. M. MAYFIELD\n_>\nMrs. C. M. Mayfield, our charming\npresident of H. B. A. Lodge No. 28\u00a3\nof Waynesboro is \"cleaning up\u201d in hei\nlodge. At the untimely death of hei\nhusband, she was elected president\nand may I say, she has really BEEN\nACTING PRESIDENT.\nIn the March board she reported a\nrot?l of 126 members. Hurrah, tc\nSister Mayfield.\nJ-i the March board she reported a\nt 1 of 126 members. Hurrah, tc\nI Sister Mayfield.\nI* Laundry Mark\" Sleuth\nt NASSAU CUUNrY v v 'tL. p.dice Captain Adani Yulch'\nhas taken the dividend. i in .r omnv a lawbreaker Tho\nNassau police officer i the F P I on his specialty,\ntraces criminals thr. .m their clothes For instance, I\nif a thug binds hi. e 1 1 m marked handkerchi* f\n4 Yulch can check thnn, i i> nt ilication, and usual I\nhave the man arrested within e\nThe recent murder of \\u i I Suzanne Uegnan in Chicago/!\nhinged in its solution or. the .pie. ion c v e e..\u00ab-d;. j\nthe American Institute of Laundering The n r.j.-i.-i\nchief marked with the name of a man who, it turned out,\nBut Yulch usually can \u201cget his man.\" Even the new invisible i\nIniarks, now used by some laundryow u rs reu.e to life as n\nFOLK WE\nKNOW\nReverend Lewis Moore, our presi\ndent at Waynesboro, was in the office\nthis week on business.\nProfessor Wm Hopkins continues\non the sick list. He is a patient in a\nlocal hospital in the city.\nMrs. Willie Collins underwent tVe\nsecond operation this week in Ander\nson's Infirmary. She is pretty rest\nless as we go to press.\nDR. COLEMAN IN HOSPITAL\nDr. R. L. Coleman with offices ir\nthe H. B. A. office building is in tht\nhospital in Nashville, Tenn. H i s\nmany, many patients, friends and ad\nmirers are praying that he will soot\nrecover.\nTO BE WITH LODGE NO. 55\nON SECOND SUNDAY\nThe General Secretary, Reverend R\ni L. Young, will be with Lodge No. 7>;\nI of Ellisville, Floyd Goins, President\non the second Sunday in April. Rev\nYoung will preach the annual sermoi\nfor the lodge.\nA big time is in store for thi\nlarge number of friends and visitor\nwho plan to attend this meeting.\nGENERAL PRESIDENT TO VISE\nLOU IN ON 8th OF MAY\nBrother J. S. Simmons and hi\nmembers and friends are anticipatini\na big time for the 8th of May a\nwhich time the General President wil\nbe present and deliver the main ad\ndress.\nLodge No. 487 is moving along nice\nly and we feel that the General Pres\nident will render us yeoman servici\non the 8th of May.\nThe general public is cordially in\nvited to attend this meeting.\nJ. S. Simmons, President\nEXECUTIVE BOARD, ETC., BIG\nFACTORS\nWithout a shadow of a doubt, the\nConvention made the best progressive\nmove last July that has been made in\nthe history of the organization. -The\norganizing of an Executive Board that\nhas general control; the organizing of\ni Standing Committee in reality and\nthe election of a real Trustee Board\nhave meant new life to this Associa\ntion.\nThe various persons who head these\ndifferent Boards are not figure-heads\nnor puppets. They are.ueal represen\ntatives of our organization.\nWith the General President with\nyears of worthwhile experience; the\nGeneral Vice President who possesses\na coolness and calmness of spirit un\nder fire; a General Secretary with\ncourage and manhood who has nevei\nfailed and a General Treasurer who\nis a sound thinker and sane counsel\nlor. These four General Officers, as\nrequired by our Constitution, backer\nun with an Executive Board with A\nI Barnett at the head and a Stand\nuittee with G. B. Arringtor\nGliding like (he Rock o1\nGibraltar SUCCESS IS OURS\nMRS. MABEL KENDRICK\n1 at\nMrs. Mabel Kendrick, president of\nH. B. A. Lodge No. 121 who is wide\nawake a n d alert. The Association\nmade no mistake in electing her a\nmember of the Executive Board.\nIt is a fine thing for us to be liberal\nenough to give our women recogni\ntion in some of these all important\nplaces.\nIMPORT \\NT*TO PRESIDENTS\nV\nDear Presidents: The office is happy\nto know that you are interested in\nyour lodge and your financial reports\nto the extent that you try to keep up\nwith everything pertaining to the\noffice and your local lodge.\nPermit your Secretary to make this\nobservation: As you know, the board\nclosed March 5th. You also know\nthat we are doing in one day in the\nboard what wTe used to do in from\nfive to seven days.\nSome of you seem to feel that with\nonly two persons in the office to do\nthe work that we should be able to\nwrite hundreds of receipts, check your\nreport blanks with almost seven\nthousand members, which are to be\nchecked and double checked; issue a\nlarge number of policies for new\nmembers that are made in the board;\nthe Weekly Echo to be published\nt weekly; hundreds of persons coming\n1 to the office regularly on II. B. A.\nj business matters and we must stop\nand listen at them discuss their\nproblems; the daily mail that comes\nto our office from two to three times\nper day; keep our death roll straight;\nnotify each of you of any members\nwhom you failed to pay for in the\nBoard, together with numerous other j\nmatters and more in less than thirty\ndays.\nMay I say to you that it cannot be\ndone. Permit me to suggest this t<\nyou: When you mail in your report i\nand get your post office receipt or j\nwhen you come to the board and make\nyour repot t personally a n d get oui j\nofficii 1 iveolpt ant then yoiu- rc\" vt\nis pubiisned through the Weekly Echo\nthat should give you and your lodg\" j\nto \u2019now that your report has been\nmade. Please do not expect the office\nto do the impossible.\nWhen you get a post office money\norder and then when your report is\npublished through the Echo that is\ntwo receipts within itself and it will\nbe mighty sweet of you if some of\nyou would not rush us with cards and\nletters about a third receipt. Give\nus time if you please.\nMR. G. E. ANDERSON\nMr. G. E. Anderson of Shuqualak,\npresident of H. B. A. Lodge No. 93\nhas been in poor health for some\ntime and we wish to doff our hats to\nhim for being able to hold his mem\nbers together so nicely, add new mem\nbers a n d make round reports in the\nboards. In the March Board Brother\nAnderson reported f o r ninety one\nmembers. This is going some, Bro.\nIG. E. You and \u201cShellie\" know how\nI to do big things.\nOn Unemployment\nJL J\nBy Ruth Taylor\nUnemployment is the big problem\nof today. But this great problem is\nnot an issue in which we have only a\nselfish interest. Unemployment in\nAmerica will affect the whole world.\nAs Walter Lippmann said, \u201cWe are\nnow such a preponderant part of the\neconomy of the world that unless\nhere at home we attain the stability\nof full employment, we shall be a\nfoi'ce for disorder, rather than for\norder everywhere.\u201d\nWe have learned the bitter lesson\nthat no democracy is secure anywhere\nin the world when tyranny reigns\nanywhere in the world. Wo have\nlearned the bitter lesson that not only\ncan no nation remain half slave and\nhalf free\u2014but that no world can re\nmain half slave and half free.\nDo we need another bitter lesson\nto learn that there can be no endur\ning prosperity for one country and\nnot for all? Freedom of body is\nsmall solace to a hungry man. Pat\nriotism does not thrive on hunger.\nUnless we establish in all countries a\nsystem removing the shadow of hun\nger from anyone that is willing to\nwork, there will be no freedom any\nwhere.\n1 am not advocating ar.y system of\nworld philanthropy. But 1 am say\ning that full employment here in\nAmerica is not just a question of\nearning a living for us alone. We\nmust prove here in America that in\ndemocracy lies the solution of the\npeace problems, that we can not only\nmaintain our freedom of thought bul\nwith our American system of fra\nenterprise we can continue our high\nstandards of living and wipe out the\ndread spectre of unemployment, oi\npost-war depression. We must prove\nthe worth of our faith in our way ol\nlife, if we want to make a perma\nnent peace.\nIf we will all work together, we\ncan lick this spectre and win a rem\nanent peace of prosperity. We must\nprove that 1 HO,000.000 people stem\nming from all the four corners of the\nearth can live together and togethei\ncreate a real Democracy w here a\nworker, whether oi brain or he d, i3\nan Amoricm worker, not an Irish\nworker, not a Polish worker, not an\nItalian worker, not a Jewish worker,\na Catholic worker, a Protestant work\ner, but just an American.\nDonuts' and MolassU\nj 'e1 Peppermint Milk'\nWith the 9th annual National]\nDonut Week being observed]\nthroughout the country from March}\n24th through 30th, here is a newV\nand novel way to serve store boughil\nidonuts. Put 2 tablespoons molasses]\nin glass; till with milk; stir ti j\ni blend. Add 1 to 2 drops pepper 5\nj mint extract to taste. Dust with]\n'nutmeg. Serve with sugared donuts!\njfor an after school snack. This is a\n'nutritious as well as delicious dish\nPRESIDENT WM. BELL\nPresident Wm. Bell of H. B. A.\nLodge No. 31 of Lauderdale was in\nthe office this week with some more\napplication blanks for new members.\nFor many, many years it seemed as\nif Mr. Bell was \"stuck\" and could not\ni go any farther.\nWe have gone to his records and\nchecked up on the members added\nsince September 1945 and we are\nhappy to state that he has added\ntwenty-two new members. The office\nwishes to congratulate Brother Bell\nj on proving to us that he was not\n\"stuck\". He seemed to have been\nwaiting for something U> encourage\nhim to come out of that \"rut\". Keep\nthe good work up. Brother Bell, we\nknew it was in you.\nI\nCOTTON TIME\nPick your cotton early,\n\u2019cause cotton is such won-j\n(1 erful stuff! Once upon a'\ntime you loved it because1\nit was clean and cool and,\ncolorful. And it\u2019s still\nthat, but it has taken on\nbig city airs, too. It\u2019s\nstyled with an air for\nyoung tricks who go places\nand do things.\nHomespun-textured cot^l\nton, woven in the mills of\nour good neighbor, Mexi\nco, lends its charm to this\nFashion Frock of the\nWeek. The corselet mid\n\u2022riff, accented by conga line\nbuttons, gives an exciting\nhand-span waistline above\nthe dirndl skirt of this\ngay, young SweeTeen. The\nhigh, round neck is bound\nand ties in a shoestring\nbow, and the facing of the\nsleeves folds back and but\ntons to shyly but surely\nexpose nice arms.\nCotton is oh-so e-'v to\ntub and oh-oh\non Miss Fashion\nallowance!","height":"25312","width":"18864"}}
